<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="381" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="381">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="381">
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. pruinosus" pageId="0" pageNumber="381" rank="species" species="pruinosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="381">P. pruinosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widespread synanthropic species of Mediterranean origin, currently known from many European and American countries, as well as in Transcaucasia and Pakistan (
<bibRefCitation author="Schmalfuss, H" journalOrPublisher="Serie A" pageId="0" pageNumber="381" pagination="1 - 341" refId="B12" refString="Schmalfuss, H, 2003. World catalog of terrestrial isopods (Isopoda: Oniscidea). Stuttgarter Beitraege zur Naturkunde. Serie A 654: 1 - 341" title="World catalog of terrestrial isopods (Isopoda: Oniscidea). Stuttgarter Beitraege zur Naturkunde." volume="654" year="2003">Schmalfuss 2003</bibRefCitation>
, Kuznetsova &amp; Gongalsky 2012, 
<bibRefCitation author="Kazmi, QB" journalOrPublisher="International Journal of Biological Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="381" pagination="45 - 47" refId="B3" refString="Kazmi, QB, 2015. Report of Porcellionides pruinosus (Brandt, 1833) (Isopoda, Oniscidea, Porcellionidae) from Karachi, Pakistan. International Journal of Biological Research 3 (1): 45 - 47" title="Report of Porcellionides pruinosus (Brandt, 1833) (Isopoda, Oniscidea, Porcellionidae) from Karachi, Pakistan." volume="3" year="2015">Kazmi 2015</bibRefCitation>
). In European part of Russia this species has previously been found in central and southern parts of the country. It was also known from Siberia (Kuznetsova &amp; Gongalsky 2012, 
<bibRefCitation author="Khisametdinova, DD" journalOrPublisher="Invertebrate Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="381" pagination="51 - 55" refId="B4" refString="Khisametdinova, DD, Nefediev, PS, Tuf, IH, 2016. New records of woodlice in the south of western Siberia, Russia (Isopoda: Oniscidea). Invertebrate Zoology 13 (1): 51 - 55" title="New records of woodlice in the south of western Siberia, Russia (Isopoda: Oniscidea)." volume="13" year="2016">Khisametdinova et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Nefediev, PS" journalOrPublisher="Arthropoda Selecta" pageId="0" pageNumber="381" pagination="33 - 36" refId="B7" refString="Nefediev, PS, Gongalsky, KB, Lebedev, YuM, Efimov, DA, 2018. Addition to the fauna of synanthropic woodlice in the south of Western Siberia, Russia (Isopoda: Oniscidea). Arthropoda Selecta 27 (1): 33 - 36" title="Addition to the fauna of synanthropic woodlice in the south of Western Siberia, Russia (Isopoda: Oniscidea)." volume="27" year="2018">Nefediev et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
). The nearest localities of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. pruinosus" pageId="0" pageNumber="381" rank="species" species="pruinosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="381">P. pruinosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are registered in Poland, Ukraine and the European part of Russia. The distribution of this species is associated with human settlements and dung heaps as compost substance keeps the warm temperature during winter periods (
<bibRefCitation author="Cawley, M" journalOrPublisher="The Irish Naturalists' Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="381" pagination="273 - 277" refId="B1" refString="Cawley, M, 1996. The woodlice (Crustacea, Isopoda) of Cos Sligo and Leitrim. The Irish Naturalists' Journal 25 (8): 273 - 277" title="The woodlice (Crustacea, Isopoda) of Cos Sligo and Leitrim." volume="25" year="1996">Cawley 1996</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="381" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="381">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="381">
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. pruinosus" pageId="0" pageNumber="381" rank="species" species="pruinosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="381">P. pruinosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known to exhibit patterns of geographical variation between populations, and has been suspected to consist of several very closely related species (
<bibRefCitation author="Salzat, A" journalOrPublisher="Heredity" pageId="0" pageNumber="381" pagination="428 - 443" refId="B11" refString="Salzat, A, Cordaux, MR, Bouchon, D, 2001. Wolbachia diversity in the Porcellionides pruinosus complex of species (Crustacea: Oniscidea): evidence for host-dependent patterns of infection. Heredity 87 (4): 428 - 443" title="Wolbachia diversity in the Porcellionides pruinosus complex of species (Crustacea: Oniscidea): evidence for host-dependent patterns of infection." volume="87" year="2001">Salzat et al. 2001</bibRefCitation>
). Ten subspecies are recognized. Recent investigations have suggested that some morphologically similar populations may consist of separate species. For example, the previously reported single North American species 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. pruinosus" pageId="0" pageNumber="381" rank="species" species="pruinosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="381">P. pruinosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in fact consisted from two separate species. Although these species had subtle physiological and morphological differences, they were electrophoretically, reproductively, and distributionally distinct (Garthwaite &amp; Sassaman 1985). Formally, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. pruinosus" pageId="0" pageNumber="381" rank="species" species="pruinosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="381">P. pruinosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other species by the extent of white bands at the antennae. We supposed that world taxonomic status of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. pruinosus" pageId="0" pageNumber="381" rank="species" species="pruinosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="381">P. pruinosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be re-evaluated.
</paragraph>
